Bot Deployment & Management Commands
Introduction
This document contains a comprehensive list of commands to manage and deploy your Discord bot in an SSH environment.
1. Git Commands
1.1 Update Your Bot
Command to update the bot with the latest changes from the main branch:
```bash
git pull origin main
```
Description: Pulls the latest changes from the main branch of your repository.
1.2 Commit Changes
Command to commit changes to your local repository:
```bash
git add .
git commit -m "Your commit message here"
git push origin main
```
Description: Adds all changes, commits them with a message, and pushes them to the main branch of your repository.
1.3 Clone the Repository
Command to clone the repository to your machine:
```bash
git clone https://github.com/your-username/ELBOT.git
```
Description: Clones the repository to your machine.
2. Bot Management Commands
2.1 Start the Bot
Command to start the bot as a systemd service:
```bash
sudo systemctl start elbot.service
```
Description: Starts the bot as a systemd service.
2.2 Stop the Bot
Command to stop the bot:
```bash
sudo systemctl stop elbot.service
```
Description: Stops the bot from running.
2.3 Restart the Bot
Command to restart the bot service:
```bash
sudo systemctl restart elbot.service
```
Description: Restarts the bot to apply any changes or restart if it’s unresponsive.
2.4 Check Bot Status
Command to check the current status of the bot's systemd service:
```bash
sudo systemctl status elbot.service
```
Description: Checks the current status of the bot's systemd service.
2.5 Enable Bot to Start on Boot
Command to ensure the bot starts on system boot:
```bash
sudo systemctl enable elbot.service
```
Description: Ensures the bot automatically starts on system boot.
2.6 Disable Bot from Starting on Boot
Command to disable the bot from starting automatically on system boot:
```bash
sudo systemctl disable elbot.service
```
Description: Disables the bot from automatically starting on system boot.
3. System Monitoring Commands
3.1 View Logs for the Bot
Command to view the latest logs for the bot:
```bash
journalctl -u elbot.service --no-pager | tail -50
```
Description: Displays the most recent 50 lines of logs for the bot.
3.2 Monitor Bot's Resource Usage
Command to monitor system resources:
```bash
top
```
Description: Monitors CPU, memory, and other system resources used by running processes.
4. File Management Commands
4.1 Edit Files with Nano
Command to open a file for editing:
```bash
nano /path/to/file.py
```
Description: Opens the specified file in the `nano` text editor for editing.
4.2 Move Files
Command to move a file:
```bash
mv /path/to/source /path/to/destination
```
Description: Moves a file from the source location to the destination.
4.3 Copy Files
Command to copy a file:
```bash
cp /path/to/source /path/to/destination
```
Description: Copies a file from the source location to the destination.
4.4 List Files in a Directory
Command to list files in a directory:
```bash
ls /path/to/directory
```
Description: Lists the contents of a directory.
4.5 Change Directory
Command to change the directory:
```bash
cd /path/to/directory
```
Description: Changes the current directory to the specified path.
5. Virtual Environment Management
5.1 Activate the Virtual Environment
Command to activate the virtual environment:
```bash
source /path/to/venv/bin/activate
```
Description: Activates the virtual environment where your bot’s dependencies are installed.
5.2 Install Dependencies from `requirements.txt`
Command to install dependencies:
```bash
pip install -r requirements.txt
```
Description: Installs all Python dependencies listed in the `requirements.txt` file.
5.3 Deactivate the Virtual Environment
Command to deactivate the virtual environment:
```bash
deactivate
```
Description: Deactivates the current virtual environment.
6. Bot Deployment Script
6.1 Run Deployment Script
Command to run the deployment script:
```bash
./deploy.sh
```
Description: Executes the `deploy.sh` script that updates and restarts the bot.
6.2 Make the Deployment Script Executable
Command to make the `deploy.sh` script executable:
```bash
chmod +x deploy.sh
```
Description: Makes the `deploy.sh` script executable if it’s not already.
Final Notes
Make sure to check the logs after performing any task like updating or restarting the bot to confirm that everything is working as expected.


